<BaseLayout
  title="Why MIAR starts with cadence, not classification"
  description="A MIAR editorial note on why repeated observation, comparison, and evidence chains matter more than a single classification result."
  current="blogs"
>
  <main class="subpage-shell article-shell">
    <p class="eyebrow">Launch note</p>
    <h1>Why MIAR starts with cadence, not classification</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The easiest way to make imagery AI look impressive is to show a single
      clean image and a strong classification result. That is also one of the
      fastest ways to build the wrong product.
    </p>

    <article class="article-body">
      <p>
        MIAR starts from a different premise. The real operational asset is not
        one beautiful image. It is repeated observation. It is knowing what a
        place looked like before, what it looks like now, what changed, and how
        strongly that change can be defended.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is why cadence matters so much. A model that can name an aircraft
        in one scene is useful. A system that can repeatedly revisit an
        installation, track arrivals and departures, and carry the resulting
        evidence into a stronger review workflow is much more valuable.
      </p>
      <p>
        In that sense, MIAR is not only a classifier. It is a sensing layer
        with memory. Scenes belong to sequences, detections belong to evidence
        chains, and claims should remain separate from accepted truth until
        review happens.
      </p>
      <p>
        The product becomes more powerful when scene provenance, review state,
        analyst context, and operational meaning can travel together.
      </p>
      <p>
        MIAR starts with cadence not because classification is unimportant, but
        because cadence is what turns imagery into intelligence instead of
        isolated output.
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
